Drug patent: 20 years (including trials)
Generic drug: non-proprietary, after patent expiration
Drug development: research and registration, ~10 years
Research phases
- preclinical: non-human subjects
- phase I: 20-100 subjects, test safety
- phase II: 100-300 subjects, test efficacy and side effects
- phase III: 300-3000 subjects, test effectiveness
Registration: FDA in USA, EMA in EU
Blinded trial: prevent biases
- Single-blind: only patient blind to treatment
- Double-blind: researcher and patient blind
- Unblinding: person deducing whether treatment group
- Treatment group: receive treatment
- Control group: receive placebo
- Placebo: treatment replacement for control group
- Active placebo: produces noticeable effects
Attrition: dropout of trial participants
Intention-to-treat (ITT) analysis: results analysis based on initial assignment (include dropouts)
Eroom's law: drug discovery is slower and more expensive despite new technology (opposite of Moore's law)

#Activity
Agonist: activates receptor
Antagonist: blocks receptor
Inverse agonist: action opposite to agonist
Efficacy: functional response of drug compared to endogenous agonist
- Superagonist: >100%
- Full: 100
- Partial: 0-100
- Silent: 0
- Inverse: <0

ADME: absorption, distribution, metabolism, excretion
- drug levels and kinetics

#Absorption: administration site to action site
Dosage
- capsule: powder/pellets in shell
- tablet: solid pill
Administration method
- Intravenous: into vein
- Inhalation: breathing
- Peroral: ingestion
- Sublingual: under tongue
- Dermatological: skin
- Intramuscular
- Rectal: anus
- Subcutaneous: under skin

#Metabolism
First pass effect: reduction in drug concentration
- oral dose needs to be higher if reduction is high
- metabolism by enzymes in intestines and liver
- uptake and gradual release in lungs for lipophilic
- high for e.g. insulin, diazepam, ethanol, lidocaine, morphine

#Pharmacokinetics: plasma concentration in time
- longer elimination decreases fluctuations
- shorted dosing interval decreases fluctuations
- cumulative balance requires ~3x elimination half-time
Dose: amount administered
Dosing interval: time between administrations
Bioavailability: available percentage of drug, depends on administration
Fluctuation: change within one dosing interval
Absorption half-life
Elimination half-life
Effective dose (ED50): concentration causing response in 50%
Toxic dose (TD50): concentration causing toxicity in 50%
Lethal dose (LD50): concentration causing death in 50%

#Side effect
adverse reaction: genetic factors, allergies
selectivity: binding of drug to specific cells
specificity: drug action directly on receptor
drug interaction: caused by other drugs or food (grapefruit)
- additive: sum of two
- synergistic: more than sum of two
- antagonistic: less than sum of two
frequency
- very common: <1/10
- common: <1/100
- uncommon: <1/1000
- rare: <1/10000
- very rare: <1/100000

#Adverse reactions
Severe cutaneous adverse reactions (SCAR): type IV
- affect skin and mucous membranes, blisters, peeling skin
- Toxic epidermal necrolysis (TEN): more severe
- Stevens–Johnson syndrome (SJS): less severe
Maculopapular rash (MPR): small red bumps on skin, type IV

#Food interactions
Avocado: inductor
Broccoli: inductor
Grapefruit: inhibitor
Soya: inhibitor
Garlic: antiplatelet
Ginger: anticoagulant

#Asparaginase
enzyme breaking down asparagine
used to tread lymphoblastic leukemia, many side effects

#Amphetamine
CNS stimulant, improves congnitive control
recreational drug, addictive

#Anxiolytics: reduce anxiety
Barbiturates: depressant, general anesthesia
Benzodiazepines: depressant, GABAA agonist
- Diazepam
- Lorazepam

#Muscle relaxant
Baclofen: GABAB agonist, oral
Dantrolene: ryanodine antagonist
=non-depolarizing: require controlled respiration
Pancuronium: euthanasia
Vecuronium: general anesthesia
Atracurium: general anesthesia
Cisatracurium: general anesthesia
Rocuronium: intubation
=depolarizing
Suxamethonium/Succinylcholine: blocks acetylcholine, short term for intubation, intravenous

#Xanthines
Caffeine: CNS stimulant
Theobromine

#Lysergic acid diethylamide (LSD)
psychedelic, hallucinations
recreational drug

#Antimalarial
Artemisinin
- contains peroxide ring
- treatment of malaria and parasitic worms
Quinine:
- treatment of malaria
- less used due to serious side effects
Chloroquine: 
- treatment of malaria and lupus
- less used for malaria due to drug resistance

#Antiparasitics
Albendazole: helminths
Mebendazole: helminths
Praziquantel: helminths
Ivermectin: helminths, mites, lice
Permethrin: mites, lice
Metronidazole: protozoa
Tinidazole: protozoa
Nitazoxanide: protozoa

#Antibiotics
Penicillin: inhibits cell wall synthesis
Cephalosporin: inhibits cell wall synthesis
Erythromycin: inhibits protein synthesis
Streptomycin: inhibits protein synthesis
Tetracycline: inhibits protein synthesis

#Vaccines: activate acquired immunity
Attenuated: contain weakened live pathogen
Inactivated: contain destroyed pathogen
Subunit: contain fragments of pathogen
Conjugate: combine weak and strong antigen
Heterotypic: similar pathogen of another animal (cowpox/smallpox)
Genetic
- viral: use safe virus to insert pathogen gene
- mRNA: RNA packaged in nanoparticles
- DNA
Experimental
- dendritic cell
- recombinant
Mandatory/recommended
- rotavirus
- diphtheria
- tetanus
- pertussis
- hepatitis B
- haemophilus influenzae B
- pneumococcal (Prevnar)
- meningococcal
- polio
- measles
- mumps
- rubella
- varicella (Varivax)
Optional
- influenza
- corona (Comirnaty)
- HPV (Gardasil)
- tuberculosis
- encephalitis
- yellow fever

#History
Fialuridine: failed hepatitis B treatment, caused liver failure [1993]
Theralizumab (TGN1412): failed immunomodulator, caused organ failure [2006]

#Drugs
Humira: monoclonal antibody (autoimmune diseases)
Keytruda: humanized antibody (cancer)
Paxlovid: covid-19
Eliquis: anticoagulant
Eylea: macular edema
Revlimid: myeloma
Stelara: monoclonal antibody
Dupixent: allergies
Imbruvica: leukemia
Opdivo: cancer
Darzalex: myeloma
Trikafta: cystic fibrosis
Xarelto: anticoagulant

#Antithrombotic
=Anticoagulant: reduce blood clotting
- Heparin: activates antithrombin
- Aspirin (acetylsalicylic acid, ASA, {C6}(-COOH)-O-C(=O)-C): inactivates cyclooxygenase
- Hirudin: thrombin inhibitor, in leeches
- Apixaban: common, factor Xa inhibitor
- Rivaroxaban: factor Xa inhibitor
Coumarins: vitamin K antagonist
- Warfarin
Thrombolytic: target fibrin
- Streptokinase: produced by Streptococci, risk of antibodies
- Urokinase
- Alteplase: intravenous, recombinant DNA
=Antiplatelet: P2Y ADP antagonist, reduce platelet aggregation
- Clopidogrel
- Prasugrel
- Ticagrelor

#Antidiabetic
Insulin: common
For type 2:
- Gliclazide (Diamicron)
- Empagliflozin (Jardiance)
- Metformin (Glucophage): common
- Dulaglutide (Trulicity)

